<article id="node-17031">
<h1 >3.4.10.80 RASF - Sugarcane Farmer Retains an Interest in the Home</h1>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> THIS SCHEME CLOSED on 12 July 2007 and the following INFORMATION is FOR HISTORICAL PURPOSES ONLY.</p>
<h2>Effect on sugarcane farm (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/s/405">1.1.S.405</a>) value</h2>
<p>If the farmer retains a life, freehold or leasehold interest in the home, the value is excluded from the calculation of the value of the farm and assets, as long as the area of land retained does NOT exceed 2 hectares. This also applies if the income support recipient excises the house and curtilage (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/a/58">1.1.A.58</a>) from the remainder of the farm to retain ownership of that portion.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Excision will only apply where local zoning laws permit it.</p>
</div>
<p>A short-term lease or rental agreement does NOT satisfy this provision. In this case, the house and curtilage would be INCLUDED in the value of the sugarcane farm and farm assets.</p>
<p>The following table explains how the farmer's interest in the house should be confirmed:</p>
<table><thead><tr><th scope="col">If the interest is…</th>
<th scope="col">Then…</th>
</tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>a life interest,</td>
<td>there is no legal requirement for the interest to be documented.
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Income support recipients with a life interest would be advised to protect their interest by obtaining a written agreement, although there is no legal requirement for them to do so.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr><tr><td>freehold,</td>
<td>a copy of the certificate of title should be sought.</td>
</tr><tr><td>leasehold,</td>
<td>a copy of the written leasehold agreement between the eligible descendant and the farmer should be sought.
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> This would apply to properties subject to a pastoral or other long-term transferable leasehold arrangement.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr></tbody></table><h2>Effect on farmer when they retain an interest in the home</h2>
<p>A farmer who retains an interest in the home is treated as a homeowner (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/h/75">1.1.H.75</a>), and the value of the house and curtilage are exempt when calculating their assets. The following table explains the treatment in other situations:</p>
<table><thead><tr><th scope="col">If the farmer…</th>
<th scope="col">Then…</th>
</tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>later vacates the house,</td>
<td>the value of the life interest will be included as an asset, subject to the usual rules on temporary vacations or vacation to enter a nursing home (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/n/140">1.1.N.140</a>).</td>
</tr><tr><td>formally relinquishes the life interest,</td>
<td>the deprivation provisions will apply.</td>
</tr></tbody></table><p>A life interest under <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#rasf" title="Retirement assistance for sugarcane farmers scheme">RASF</a> is NOT a granny flat right.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../guide-social-security-law/4/1">4.1</a> Deprivation of Income &amp; Assets, <a href="../guide-social-security-law/4/6/3">4.6.3</a> Assessing the Principal Home, <a href="../guide-social-security-law/4/6/4">4.6.4</a> Assessing Special Residences &amp; Aged Accommodation</p>
</div>
